This is a classic AWS S3 behavior with Next.js exported apps!

When Next.js exports your app, it generates files like `out/chat.html`. However, your links say `<Link href="/chat">`. 
When you click it, Next.js tries to navigate there, but AWS S3 looks for an object named `chat` (with no extension). S3 gets confused, throws a hidden 404 error, and because you set the Error Document to `index.html` during the bucket setup, it just reloads the main dashboard page instead!

### The Fix
I just updated your `next.config.mjs` to include **`trailingSlash: true`**.

This tells Next.js to export your pages into folders like `out/chat/index.html` and automatically updates all your internal links to `/chat/`. AWS S3 natively understands trailing slashes and knows to instantly serve the `index.html` inside that folder!

### What you need to do:
Because we changed the configuration, you just need to rebuild and re-upload the files to S3:

1. Stop your local `npm run dev` server if it's running.
2. Run a fresh build:
   ```bash
   npm run build
   ```
3. Go back to your AWS S3 Console.
4. Delete the old files in your bucket (or just overwrite them).
5. Drag and drop the contents of your newly built `out/` folder into the bucket.

Try clicking the links on your live website again. They should instantly load the new pages without refreshing!

